Exercise 1: Findings of the above problem and the graphs are shown below:

1.1. Variable: moral integration

skewness: -0.01912821. A skewness value of -0.01912821 means that the data is slightly left-skewed.

non-normality: From Shapiro-Wilk normality test, p-value = 0.8263. So, the distribution is normal.

multiple modes: From Hartigans’ dip test, p-value = 0.8658. So, the distribution is unimodal.

Unusual values: From the boxplot, it can be seen that there are no unusual values.

Variable: ethnic hetero geneity

skewness: 1.226228. A skewness value of 1.226228 indicates that a data set is positively skewed.

non-normality: From Shapiro-Wilk normality test, p-value = 2.563e-05. So, the distribution is not normal.

multiple modes: From Hartigans’ dip test, p-value = 0.9922. So, the distribution is unimodal.

Unusual values: From the boxplot, it can be seen that there are three unusual values.

Variable: geographic mobility

skewness: 0.4120319. A skewness value of 0.4120319 indicates that a data set is positively skewed, but to a lesser extent.

non-normality: From Shapiro-Wilk normality test, p-value = 0.1915. So, the distribution is normal.

multiple modes: From Hartigans’ dip test, p-value = 0.7713.So, the distribution is unimodal.

Exercise 2: Findings of the above problem and the graphs are shown below:

2.1 Variable: moral integration by region

skewness: 1. E=0.0138, 2. MW=-0.479, 3. S=-0.270, 4. W= 0.0886; Skewness value E=0.0138 and W= 0.0886 indicate that they are almost not skewed. Skewness value MW=-0.47 and S=-0.270 indicate that they are slightly negatively skewed.

non-normality: From Shapiro-Wilk normality test, 1. E=0.9820727, 2. MW= 0.5665098, 3. S=0.1469088, 4. W=0.9725267. All of them are more than 5%. So, their distribution are normal.

multiple modes: As there are not more than one peak or central location in the box plots, so all of them are unimodal.

2.2 Variable: prestige by type

skewness: 1. bc=0.0547, 2. prof=0.374, 3. wc=0.676, 4. NA= -0.0348; Skewness value bc=0.0547 and NA= -0.0348 indicate that they are almost not skewed. Skewness value prof=0.374 and wc=0.676 indicate that they are slightly positively skewed.

non-normality: From Shapiro-Wilk normality test, 1. bc=0.2426787, 2. prof= 0.5404199, 3. wc=0.5508259. All of them are more than 5%. So, their distribution are normal.

2.3 Variable: infant mortality by region

skewness: 1. Africa=0.649, 2. Americas=2.13, 3. Asia=2.92, 4. Europe=1.46; Skewness value, Africa=0.649 indicates that this is slightly positively skewed. Skewness values, Americas=2.13, Asia=2.92 and Europe=1.46 indicate that they are strongly positively skewed.

non-normality: From Shapiro-Wilk normality test, 1. Africa=2.258847e-01, 2. Americas= 3.503233e-04, 3. Asia=1.992767e-07, 4.Europe=1.329564e-03. All of them are less than 5%. So, their distribution are not normal.

multiple modes: As there are not more than one peak or central location in the box plots, so all of them are unimodal.

  2. Independent-samples tt-test (NOTE: law will first need to be recoded as a factor).

Point-biserial correlation: The point-biserial correlation coefficient between Drivers Killed and law is -0.3285051, which suggests a moderate negative correlation.The p-value is very small (p-value = 3.288e-06), indicating that this correlation is statistically significant.

Independent-samples tt-test: The t-value is 5.1253, the degrees of freedom are 29.609, and the p-value is 1.693e-05. The very low p-value indicates that the observed difference is unlikely to be due to chance, assuming the null hypothesis is true.

  1. Write a brief results narrative that includes:
    3.1. An interpretation of the slope coefficients from the regression analysis. 3.2. An interpretation of the intercept from the regression analysis.
    3.3. An interpretation of the multiple coefficient of determination (R2R2).

3.1. The slope coefficients in the multiple regression model indicate the expected change in the response variable (prestige) for a one-unit increase in the predictor variable, while holding all other predictor variables constant. The interpretation of the slope coefficients for the education and income are as following:

The estimated slope coefficient for education is 4.14. This means that, on average, each additional year of education is associated with a 4.14 unit increase in prestige, while holding income constant. The 95% confidence interval for this coefficient (0.35, 11.86) suggests that we can be reasonably confident that the true population slope falls within this range.

The estimated slope coefficient for income is 1.36. This means that, on average, each additional unit of income is associated with a 1.36 unit increase in prestige, while holding education constant. The 95% confidence interval for this coefficient (0.22, 6.07) suggests that we can be reasonably confident that the true population slope falls within this range.

3.2. The intercept in a regression model represents the expected value of the response variable (prestige) when all predictor variables are set to zero. In this model, the estimated intercept is -6.85, which means that the expected value of prestige is -6.85 when both education and income are equal to zero.

3.3. The multiple coefficient of determination,(R2R2), measures the proportion of variance in the response variable (prestige) that can be explained by the predictor variables (education and income) in the multiple regression model. In this model, the (R2R2) is 0.80, which means that approximately 80% of the variation in prestige can be explained by the linear relationship with education and income.
